sec.p:
Grieving may be ‘modified’ by a number of pre-existing ‘risk ‘factors that include:


the nature of the relationship with the deceased;

the stage in life of both the bereaved and the deceased;

the presence or absence of societal support;

the culture within which the bereavement occurs; and

the religious or secular background of the bereaved.

In addition, the circumstances surrounding the death of a loved one that impact adversely on grief include:


traumatic sudden (possibly multiple) deaths;

a lack of ‘anticipatory’ grief, that period of adjustment and preparation for an expected death of a loved one;

suicide;

homicide.

Persistent and disruptive yearning, pining and longing for the deceased with the presence of at least four out of eight of the following:


trouble accepting the death;

inability to trust others since the death;

excessive bitterness;

uneasiness about moving on with life;

detachment from those who the bereaved were previously close to;

the feeling that life is now meaningless;

the future holds no prospect for fulfilment; and

agitation since the death.

This states a number of principles that underpin bereavement care and include:


clear communication;

accurate information and knowledge appropriate to the cultural and religious needs of the bereaved;

a suitable undisturbed private environment away from the ED;

training of staff in all aspects of bereavement care;

support of staff; 

review and audit of bereavement services.

Bereavement policies specific to the ED should be in place and supported by a wider Trust policy and this should address the following:


provision of information over the telephone to relatives and friends about the dead or dying patient;

nomination of a specific member of staff to receive relatives and friends and support them throughout their time in the ED and to co-ordinate the provision of information about and access to resuscitative efforts;

access to the body of the deceased (within the requirements of the law) both within the ED and in the mortuary in the hours following death for those relatives and friends who arrive later;

organ and tissue donation;

practical information for the bereaved concerning post-mortems, the role of the Coroner and the registering of deaths; and

follow-up in the days and weeks following a death.

Potential benefits of witnessed resuscitation are as follows:


decreases grief;

relatives can speak whilst there is still a chance the patient can hear;

to satisfy the need to be with a loved one in their dying moments;

acceptance of death;

the giving of information;

promotes professionalism of staff; and

prompts staff to think of patient as a person.

Potential disadvantages of witnessed resuscitation are as follows:


increase in grief;

emotional interference, e.g., decisions to continue or terminate resuscitation;

physical interference;

breach of confidentiality;

conflict between relatives;

increased stress upon resuscitation team and impairment of performance; and

increased risk of litigation.

The study also highlighted the range of reasons for wanting and not wanting to view the body and how reactions changed over time, a finding found in previous studies (Hodgkinson, 1995; Raphael, 1997):


to identify the body to ensure there was no mistake;

to care for the dead;

to say goodbye; and

a sense of duty.

Provision of support following bereavement may be through:


family and friends;

those who had been bereaved through similar mechanisms

ED bereavement services; (This may be in the form of telephone calls, home visits, letters or visits by the bereaved to the ED, usually led by nursing staff.)

primary care (general practitioner (GP) and district nurses);

social workers;

religious organisations;

voluntary organisations; and

professional counselling services.
